Let $X_A$ be the XOR sum of a subset of $A$, and $k_A$ be its size.
Let $X_B$ be the XOR sum of a subset of $B$, and $k_B$ be its size.

We want $X_A \oplus X_B = \text{target}$.
This implies $X_B = \text{target} \oplus X_A$.

For a fixed $X_A$, we look up $X_B = \text{target} \oplus X_A$ in the results from $B$.
If we find a pair $(X_B, k_B)$ that matches, the total kept elements size is $k_A + k_B$.
We want to maximize $k_A + k_B$.

The number of elements removed is $N - (k_A + k_B)$. Minimizing removals is maximizing $k_A + k_B$.

